Have other questions? Call your school or email us at info@cuhsd.org.

We are in this together! #UnitedCUHSD

post_text:
Please join us in recognizing Patriot Day, a National Day of Service and Remembrance for the lives lost in the September 11th attacks on the World Trade Center. Today marks 19 years since 2,977 people were killed in the terrorist attacks. In honor of the lives lost on this day, flags will be flown at half-staff from sunrise to sunset at all CUHSD schools and District sites.

#NeverForget #WeRemember #PatriotDay

post_text:
September is National Suicide Prevention Awareness Month and a critical time to share resources, reach out to those affected by suicide, raise awareness and connect individuals with support and treatments. While suicide prevention is important to address year-round, Suicide Prevention Awareness Month serves as a dedicated time to come together with collective passion and strength around a difficult topic. The truth is, we can all benefit from honest conversations about mental health conditions and suicide, because just one conversation can change a life.

We are sharing resources with our community so they know they are not alone. #SuicidePrevention #stigmafree NAMI

https://www.nami.org/Get-Involved/Awareness-Events/Suicide-Prevention-Awareness-Month

post_text:
We need your input! Participate in a ThoughtExchange to provide feedback on the district's current priorities to improve distance learning for all students. Based on the latest community feedback, we are considering investing more in to the following priorities:

✅Student learning supports, including tutoring or credit recovery options
✅Student and staff technology needs, including
✅Chromebooks and wifi
✅Mental health services, including CASSY counselors
✅Teacher, student and parent/guardian training on distance learning
✅Student nutritional needs, including providing meals every day

What do you think? Let us know at https://bit.ly/thoughtexchangeaugust2020

Santa Clara County Library District - SCCLD
August 11 at 8:16 AM ·

Many schools are beginning the new academic year with distance learning. Students, as well as parents and caregivers can benefit from assistance in various subjects including math, science, or proofreading reports. Let SCCLD be your source for homework help!

All public K-12 students who live within SCCLD's boundaries can get free library eAccounts through their school (Learn more: https://bit.ly/3ijW9dA).

These eAccounts let students access all of the library's free online resources (Found here: sccld.org/online-library/).

Get live one-on-one tutoring with Brainfuse, homework help with LearningExpress, and current information from our online reference databases.

Don't have a student eAccount? Children, teens and adult learners can still benefit from the many resources available from the SCCLD online library!

Join CUHSD at the Silicon Valley Leadership Group's Education Summit 2020: Equity, Education and Talent Development Post-COVID on August 14 from 8:30am-12pm. #SVEdSummit

Register here: https://www.svlg.org/event/education-summit/?instance_id=1099

How are teachers and school administrators planning to start school in the fall? What are state legislators doing to ensure a safe, equitable education environment? What does the future of work, and learning and development look like in the wake of COVID-19, in the aftermath of George Floyd?

Education Summit 2020 will feature key decision-makers across education, government, and business in interactive sessions to address your questions, as well as topic-based networking room. We hope to see you there!

How are teachers and school administrators planning to start school in the fall? What are state legislators doing to ensure a safe, equitable education environment? What does the future of work, and learning and development look like in the wake of COVID-19, in the aftermath of George Floyd?

Education Summit 2020 will feature key decision-makers across education, government, and business in interactive sessions to address your questions, as well as topic-based networking room. We hope to see you there!

SVLG.ORG
Education Summit (2020-08-14)

post_text:
Planning Update: Superintendent Robert Bravo shared an update this evening with our community regarding the District's proposed Restarting and Recovery plan and information on an upcoming community webinar.

"When we first were told to close schools in March, we had little time to transition our entire operation to a virtual setting and shifted to emergency distance learning. We know our teachers and staff made an incredible effort to transform the way they teach, connect and support students in Spring, but more will be needed to ensure students don’t fall further behind in the upcoming year. Although online learning can never take the place of in-person learning, based on what we learned in the Spring and feedback from teachers, parents, and students, we can and we will work to make our online instructional program more robust."

Full update here: https://bit.ly/cuhsd7202020

Video message from Superintendent Bravo:
https://youtu.be/Hppl5FA4xKY

Planning Update: During the July 16, Regular Board Meeting Trustees gave direction to the Superintendent for the 2020-2021 school year and agreed to the recommendations of the Reopening Steering Committee (RSC), which includes providing online learning as the primary form of instruction for the duration of the Fall semester and work to create opportunities for in-person support for small groups of students as the semester progresses.

Superintendent Robert Bravo also shared an introduction to the District's proposed "Recovery and Restarting" Plan for the 2020-2021 school year.

Get tested! From June 22 to 26, the County of Santa Clara will be offering new COVID-19 pop-up testing sites in San José and the City of Santa Clara.

Since late May, to increase access to testing, Santa Clara Valley Medical Center has been offering diagnostic COVID-19 testing through pop-up locations around the community. The Santa Clara County Department of Public Health recommends that anyone who interacts with the public and may not always be able to maintain social distancing should be tested for COVID-19, testing is also now available for anyone who wants to be tested for COVID-19.

Visit sccfreetest.org for more information or to use an interactive map of the community, pop-up, hospital, and clinic testing sites.

#COVID19 #GetTested #SCCSchools

Get help buying food while schools are closed!
Because schools are closed due to COVID-19,
children who are eligible for free or reduced-price
meals can get up to $365 in food benefits
in addition to their pick up meals from school.
These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT
or P-EBT.

Obtenga ayuda para comprar alimentos mientras las
escuelas permanecen cerradas

Debido a que las escuelas están cerradas por la COVID-19,
los niños que califican para recibir desayunos y almuerzos
gratuitos o a precios reducidos pueden recibir hasta $365 en beneficios para comprar alimentos, además de poder recoger sus alimentos de las escuelas. A estos beneficios alimenticios se les llama «Pandemic EBT» o «P-EBT» (transferencia electrónica de beneficios por una pandemia)

post_text:
A big congratulations to CUHSD Food Service workers Alicia Contreras and Elizabeth Becerril Jimenez for receiving the first CUHSD Beating the Odds award. The award is given to district employees who accomplish the impossible during these challenging times. Alicia and Elizabeth received this award for their commitment to providing students and the CUHSD community with warm meals, six days a week during the school closures. They went from serving 2,600 meals a day on campus to serving more than 4,000 meals to our students and community in parking lots each day. So far our Food Services team has served more than 132,000 meals since the school closure!!

They both have earned our heartfelt gratitude for their impeccable leadership, positivity and collaboration to serve our community. Thank you!!
#ThankaSchoolEmployee
#StaffAppreciation

County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
May 5 at 9:01 AM ·

This Cinco de Mayo enjoy a DIY craft at home. Try making “papel picado”:

Supplies: sheets of tissue or crepe paper, scissors, tape or glue, and twine.

Directions:

1: Gather your supplies.

2: Cut tissue or crepe paper into square sheets.

3: Fold paper in half, and a half again.

4: Cut out pattern of bottom half.

5: Open it and fold down.

6: Fold diagonally and cut out shapes.

Stay home. Stay Safe.

#ApartTogetherSCC

post_text:
Branham High School teacher Fitz Vo was featured in a recent The Mercury News article that highlighted how teachers are adapting to virtual teaching while balancing family life.

The article provided insight from teachers across the Bay Area who are learning new technology while balancing the needs of their families and students. But through the isolation and difficulty, Vo talked about a silver lining.

“I know that I’m not the only person who’s going through it,” he said. “Just knowing that everyone’s in the same boat gives me a feeling of support"

Thank you to all of our teachers for your hard work and dedication during this time!

https://www.mercurynews.com/2020/04/27/virtual-teaching-on-the-job-learning-south-bay-teachers-cram-two-worlds-into-one/

The Measure AA Citizen’s Oversight Committee is looking for new members! The independent oversight committee meets quarterly to ensure the Measure AA bond money is only being spent on the facilities projects directed by the bond language.

For more information and to apply, please email Andrea Ciplickas at azc@comcast.net.

COVID-19 Update: Today the County of Santa Clara Public Health Department issued a new order extending the current Shelter-In-Place to May 3, 2020. Consistent with this order and as previously communicated, CUHSD schools will remain closed until at least May 4. If this guidance changes, it will be immediately communicated to parents, students and staff.

To adjust to the new mandates in the new order, CUHSD will also be taking the following new actions:

✅Closing access to school fields and tracks (if access has not already been closed)
✅Posting mandatory social distancing guidelines at all the school sites

Staff will continue to adhere to the social distancing guidance during technology and meal distribution.

More information: https://www.cuhsd.org/apps/pages/coronavirusinfo

shared_text:
The College Board
March 20 at 10:24 AM ·

We know the coronavirus has created challenges for AP students and teachers. Here’s how the College Board will support you during this time:

1️⃣ We’re providing free, live and on-demand AP courses

To support AP students affected by school closures due to COVID-19, students and schools will have access to live AP review lessons, delivered by AP teachers from across the country. Lessons will begin March 25.

2️⃣ We’re developing a new at-home testing option

Because of the challenges created by COVID-19, we’re developing a new at-home AP Exam option. Students will be able to test on a computer, tablet, or smartphone.

We will invest so that every AP student impacted by COVID-19 has the tools and connectivity they need to review AP content online and take the exam from home.

During this challenging time, we will work to give every AP student the opportunity to earn the college credit and placement they’ve been working toward all year while maintaining a focus on the health and safety of our AP community.

More details here: http://spr.ly/61851tbn3.

post_text:
Tonight's Regular Board Meeting will be held remotely via teleconference. Therefore, there will be no public, physical location to view the meeting. You can watch the meeting via live-stream by going to our website at the following link: https://www.cuhsd.org/apps/pages/Board_Meeting_Agendas_and_Recordings

Public comments may also be made remotely by submitting a Public Comments form, which will be located on our website and on BoardDocs 15 minutes before the Board meeting. Those that submit a public comment form will be called via telephone at the number they provided in the form. If the person does not answer, the Board President will move onto the next public comment request. Oral presentations/communications to the Board are limited to three minutes per person and twenty minutes per topic.

Thank you for your cooperation as we try to adapt to the countywide shelter-in-place, while still providing the public with an opportunity to observe and participate in Board meetings. We look forward to the time these meetings can resume to be conducted in-person.

Branham High School
March 11 at 7:20 PM ·

This past weekend, the Quizbowl Club competed in the World Scholar’s Cup.

This year, Branham continued its tradition of excellence by repeating its first place finish. A team composed of Junior Alex Goldberg and Freshmen Andrew Goldberg and Arjun Mittha took first overall and 1st in the team bowl, team writing, and the test. Juniors Alex Goldberg and Charlie Pappalardo came in first and second as individuals, among numerous awards.

Every Branham team finished in the top ten, qualifying all Branham scholars for a berth at Global Rounds from Sydney to Prague.

Branham Bear Witness is at Branham High School.
March 10 at 12:40 PM · San Jose, CA ·

The district is rolling out portable handwash stations to slow the potential spread of COVID-19, the virus that has so far infected more than 800 people in the United States, 43 of whom are in Santa Clara County, according to the Centers for Disease Control. As of Tuesday, 25 people have died in the U.S. from illnesses related to the disease. The district has responded with several preventive measures, including the stations, and has limited the number and attendance of after-school events. We highlight some of the recent developments.

Reporting by Caitlyn Schlaman and photo by Zach Macapanpan

According to the County of Santa Clara Public Health Department and the CDC, the most effective ways to reduce the spread of viruses is to:
✅ Stay home when you are sick.
✅ Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, especially after going to the bathroom; before eating; and after blowing your nose, coughing, or sneezing.
✅Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth.
✅ Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash and clean your hands.
✅ Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.

Read more on the prevention steps CUHSD is taking to stop the spread of germs in our schools here:

http://bit.ly/2Ikof8I

Please join us in recognizing our Board of Trustees as we honor Board Appreciation Month. School Boards are a crucial component of our public education systems, and our Trustees provide a critical link between our schools and our community. They establish policies, set the direction, develop a strategic vision and plan, ensure accountability and provide community leadership on behalf of the District and public education.

Thank you to Trustees Kristiina Arrasmith, Stacey Brown, Kalen Gallagher, Linda Goytia and Robert Varich for your dedication to the success of our students and staff!

#SchoolBoardAppreciationMonth #mycuhsd

shared_text:
Garvin Thomas NBC Bay Area is feeling excited.
December 22, 2019 at 8:54 PM ·

I have a big announcement ... and a favor.

For the first time in my broadcasting career, I have put together a 30-minute documentary.

It’s called Winter Wishes and airs Christmas Day at 6:30 pm on NBC Bay Area

It’s about the Winter Wishes program held at San Jose’s Branham High School each December.

I covered my first Winter Wishes rally in 2015 and have returned every year since. It is consistently one of the most uplifting and emotional experiences I get to witness.

In our documentary, we trace the history of the program, hear about the life-changing impact the wishes have, and go behind the scenes as students prepare to grant this year's wishes.

Here’s the favor part: if you could let others know about the show, I would greatly appreciate it. I really hope you enjoy it. #bayareaproud #goodnews

It’s about the Winter Wishes program held at San Jose’s Branham High School each December.

I covered my first Winter Wishes rally in 2015 and have returned every year since. It is consistently one of the most uplifting and emotional experiences I get to witness.

In our documentary, we trace the history of the program, hear about the life-changing impact the wishes have, and go behind the scenes as students prepare to grant this year's wishes.

Here’s the favor part: if you could let others know about the show, I would greatly appreciate it. I really hope you enjoy it. #bayareaproud #goodnews

Congratulations to all the teams from Westmont High School, Branham High School and Leigh High School who participated in the NextFlex FlexFactor finals. With the support of our great Project Lead the Way teachers, our students pitched innovative and industry-changing ideas to a panel of experts and took home top prizes in the competition! #FlexFactor #FutureEngineers #SiliconValleyEducation

First Place: Branham High School's team Enfire (a smart gun with a built-in locking mechanism and GPS tracking to help police officers track stolen guns)

Second Place: Westmont High School's team Hydroprotect
(a device designed to prevent hydroplaning)

Third Place: Branham High School's team Connect-a-Crop (a device focused on plant growth that communicates information to farmers)

IB Programme at Del Mar High School
November 11, 2019 at 8:48 AM ·

Save-the-Date Del Mar High School - Tuesday, December 10th - for "like. post. share. repeat. LIKE". #myDonsLife is pleased to host LIKE - an original IndieFlix film about the impact of social media on teens (and all of us!) and this technology's effect on the brain. A very powerful discussion on how we can use social media constructively, including a panel discussion after the film. shared_text:
Del Mar High School
November 9, 2019 at 6:37 PM ·

Earlier this week, 90 of our AP Government students, Principal Lopez, and 8 teachers headed to SF to see Hamilton! The students took part in the The Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History Project that brought Hamilton into the classroom as part of studies on the Founding Era, and where students completed a project related to their American History studies. The program culminated with a trip to the city to see the Musical, hear from the Hamilton Cast, and most fun was seeing Del Mar students perform with the cast! Del Mar's students and teachers were so happy to be part of the Hamilton Education Program that inspires participants to become historians, writers, musicians and performers. Thank you, Hamilton & Gilder Lehrman, for giving our students the opportunity to learn from this exciting experience. #beyondtheory learning at its best at Campbell Union High School District.

Branham Bear Witness is at Branham High School.
November 7, 2019 at 3:39 PM · San Jose, CA ·

Several dozen parents attended a talk on the dangers of vaping and drug use, hosted by the Branham PTSA and the school district. Rey Cedeno, a former San Jose police officer, educated parents on different forms of paraphernalia and potentially harmful chemicals in them. “we’re trying to help kids get off of this(vapes and rugs) and make better choices or actually more informed choices,” said Assistant Principal Rick Hayashi. “It’s becoming a bigger issue than just one group of kids.” It was the second of three talks on vaping and drug use. The third one will take place at Del Mar on Nov. 13, and will be in Spanish.⁣
⁣⁣•••⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣📷: Nolan Zils⁣
⁣⁣

Branham Bear Witness is at Branham High School.
October 28, 2019 at 3:33 PM · San Jose, CA ·

District dignitaries helped officially open Branham’s renovated pool Saturday, with catered food and a swim demonstration. The completed pool is Olympic-sized, which means that the school can finally host swim meets at home again. Swim coach Dave Mackey said that he hopes the new pool can attract swimmers deciding between Branham and Leigh in the free zone and that Branham can offer more aquatics programs, such as a water polo team. “I am happy for the school and the community,” he said. “The pool is really beautiful.”⁣
⁣•••⁣
⁣📷: Jayden Kim, with alumni photo courtesy of Dave Mackey.⁣
⁣⁣
⁣#bhsbearwitness #everyoneintothepool

October 18, 2019 at 8:22 AM · San Jose, CA ·

NBC Bay Area journalist Garvin Thomas paid a visit to the Leadership class Thursday to record a segment for Branham’s upcoming ninth annual Winter Wishes rally. The school will again be featured on the channel’s half-hour Bay Area Proud segment that he produces, centered around positive stories in the region. The Leadership class is collecting student wishes, big and small, through Oct. 25.

shared_text:
Branham Bear Witness
September 9, 2019 at 5:56 PM ·

The Bear Witness is proud to be among 39 publications nationwide named an NSPA Pacemaker finalist, considered the top honor in scholastic journalism. This is the third time the paper has been a finalist, having won the award once in 2018. Editor in chief Julianne Alvares, who has been with the paper for three years, said she is proud of its accomplishments. “I feel so honored to be a Pacemaker finalist for the third year in a row and represent Branham at the highest level,” she said. “So excited to see all the staff’s hard work pay off!” Nineteen publications will be declared Pacemaker winners, which will be announced late November at the annual conference in Washington, D.C. To view our past publications, click on the link here: https://issuu.com/bearwitness
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣•••⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣📷: National Scholastic Press Association
⁣⁣
⁣#bhsbearwitness #nspa #studentjournalism⁣
⁣

Branham Bear Witness
September 9, 2019 at 6:28 AM ·

“Going into high school as a freshman, I thought that people wouldn’t be nice to me. I remember being on campus and this one senior, Julie, would always say hi to me in the halls. There was this one day where I was feeling kind of down and she asked me, hey, are you okay? It was nice to know that she cared. Simple acts of kindness make everybody feel happier.”⁣
⁣— Ashley McDonald, sophomore⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣•••⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣📷: Jazzy Nguyen
⁣⁣

Branham Bear Witness is at Branham High School.
August 28, 2019 at 11:32 PM · San Jose, CA ·

Before district dignitaries and local officials, junior Geetanjali Jain, a student board member, cuts the ceremonial ribbon today to the new S building, marking its public debut before Branham’s Back to School Night festivities. The event featured live music, catered food and a tour of the new science facilities. The construction project is the largest renovation the school has undertaken. “This is a huge milestone in Branham’s history,” Jain said in her speech.⁣
